We reconstruct a 14-day window of the dominant Ethereum MORPHO/ETH Uniswap v4 pool and identify one sender responsible for 32 liquidity-management transactions, of which approximately 31 are normal two-band rebalances. The dominant pattern is a wide band centered near the Binance-implied MORPHO/ETH tick and a narrower one-sided secondary overlay. A prior-center drift rule fits the landed rebalance times better than the instantaneous pool/Binance gap in this window, but the trigger diagnostics are in-sample and not yet validated out of sample. The reconstruction establishes on-chain behavior and candidate mechanisms; it does not establish net LP profitability or a tradable alpha signal.
\end{abstract}
```

- **Use this section order**:

