The hard finding is that one sender repeatedly executes atomic two-band liquidity updates in this MORPHO/ETH v4 pool during the observed 14-day window. The main failure mode is address attribution: sender grouping may miss hidden ownership, shared infrastructure, or off-chain coordination.

The first inference is that the wide band \(A\) tracks the Binance-implied MORPHO/ETH tick. This fails if the current pool tick or previous \(A\)-center explains the new center equally well.

The second hypothesis is that rebalances are triggered by drift from the previous \(A\)-center. This fails if threshold crossings generate many unacted signals or do not reliably precede landed rebalances.

The third hypothesis is that band \(B\) is a one-sided secondary overlay, possibly related to inventory or directional adjustment. This fails if the side choice is indistinguishable from random under a pre-specified rule.

Net LP profitability, entity-level inventory, and tradable alpha are not established in this document.
```

